<DOC><DOCNO> AP880419-0031 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 0036EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0806 04-19 0459</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0806,0464</SECOND><HEAD>Rain Over Much of Nation, Severe Weather Injures Four in Georgia</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with damage, injuries in Georgiafrom possible tornado, picking up 4th graf ``The Ohio''</NOTE><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Rain fell over much of the country Monday, with parts of Texasreceiving almost an inch and hail the size of golf balls, whilesevere weather in Georgia damaged mobile homes and injured at leastfour people.   Showers were scattered from western Montana across the Idahopanhandle and eastern Washington and south into western Utah.Showers also reached from southern New England and southern NewYork and along the Atlantic Coast through northern Florida.   A possible tornado touched down about 9:45 p.m. at Bainbridge,Ga., said Tim Merkison, a dispatcher for the Decatur CountySheriff's Department. He said four people were hurt, though he didnot know the severity of the injuries.   About 15 mobile homes were damaged and several trees wereuprooted, he said.   The Ohio Valley, and parts of Texas and Louisiana also had rain.Thunderstorms produced 0.86 inches of rain at George West, Texas,with hail the size of golf balls west of the community and atBeeville, Texas. Strong wind knocked down trees and limbs nearBeeville.   Afternoon thunderstorms produced half-inch-diameter hail fromZachary to Watson, La. In Atlanta, 0.79 inches of rain fell in sixhours Monday, with nearly as much in Ogden, Utah.   Snowshowers continued in parts of Michigan, but the only reportof measurable snowfall during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDTwas from Mount Washington, N.H., where snow cover was 41 inchesdeep at noon.   Valentine, Neb., reached 15 degrees Monday, breaking a32-year-old record of 17 degrees. International Falls, Minn., tiedits record, 17 degrees, set in 1960.   Temperatures at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 27 degrees at Sault Ste.Marie, Mich., to 92 at McAllen, Texas. The morning low was 12degrees at both Bismarck and Fargo, N.D.   Tuesday's forecast called for snowshowers over northern Maineand rain scattered over parts of Florida and from Montana andWyoming across the northern half of the Pacific coast.   High temperatures were expected to reach the 30s and 40s overupper Michigan; 40s and 50s from New England and New Jersey, acrossthe northern Appalachians, the remainder of the Great Lakes, theupper Mississippi Valley, the northern Plains, the upper MissouriValley and the northern Rockies.   Highs in the 70s and 80s were forecast for South Carolina acrossFlorida and west over the central Gulf of Mexico states, thesouthern Plains, the desert Southwest and the inland portions ofsouthern California. High in the 60s and 70s were predicted for therest of the nation.</TEXT></DOC>